<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="section-SGOF">
    <title>Sketching Graphs of Functions</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Curve Sketching</title>
        <p>
            Consider a function <m>f(x)</m>. The function itself, and its first and second derivative, provide useful information about the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m>. From pre-calculus, we can determine,
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Points on the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m>, by evaluating <m>f</m>.</li>
            <li>The domain and range of <m>f</m>.</li>
            <li>The <m>x</m>-intercepts and <m>y</m>-intercepts.</li>
            <li>Symmetry, if the function is even or odd.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Using calculus, we can determine additional properties of a graph.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Using limits, we can determine continuity (in particular, points of discontinuity), and any vertical or horizontal asymptotes.</li>
            <li>From the first derivative <m>f'</m>, we can determine intervals of increase and decrease, and any local extrema.</li>
            <li>From the second derivative <m>f''</m>, we can determine concavity and inflection points.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Notice the importance of algebra for solving the equations <m>f(x) = 0</m> (to determine the <m>x</m>-intercepts), <m>f'(x) = 0</m> (to determine the critical points), and <m>f''(x) = 0</m> (to determine the inflection points). In summary, calculus allows us to sketch graphs of functions more accurately.
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Sketching the Graph of a Polynomial Function</title>
        <p>
            First, we will consider sketching the graph of a polynomial function <m>y = f(x)</m>. The following steps provide a good outline as to how to sketch the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li><term>Intercepts</term>. Determine any <m>x</m>-intercepts and/or the <m>y</m>-intercept, by solving the polynomial equation <m>f(x) = 0</m>, and by evaluating <m>y = f(0)</m>, respectively.</li>
            <li><term>Symmetry</term>. Determine any symmetry, i.e. if <m>f</m> is an even or odd function.</li>
            <li><term>Extrema and intervals of increase/decrease</term>. Determine <m>f'(x)</m>, and determine any critical points by solving <m>f'(x) = 0</m>, and determine any local extrema using the first or second derivative test. Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is increasing and decreasing.</li>
            <li><term>Concavity and inflection points</term>. Determine <m>f''(x)</m>, and determine any potential inflection points by solving <m>f''(x) = 0</m>. Determine the intervals where <m>f</m> is concave up or down, and use this to determine the actual inflection points.</li>
            <li>Plot the intercepts, critical points, and inflection points. Recall that critical points indicate horizontal tangents, and inflection points indicate changing concavity.</li>
            <li><term>Polynomial end behavior</term>. Consider the end behavior of <m>f</m>, i.e. the behavior of <m>f</m> as <m>x \to \infty</m> and <m>x \to -\infty</m>.</li>
            <li>Use all preceding information to determine the overall shape of the graph. If necessary, plot additional points.</li>
            <li>Finally, connect the points with a smooth curve.</li>
        </ol>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Quadratic Functions (Parabolas)</title>
        <p>
            Consider a quadratic function <m>f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c</m>. You might recall from pre-calculus that the vertex of this parabola is <m>\brac{-\frac{b}{2a}, f\brac{-\frac{b}{2a}}}</m>. This is made clear using calculus.
        </p>
        <p>
            Determining critical points, <m>f'(x) = 2ax + b = 0</m>, so <m>x = -\frac{b}{2a}</m>. Using the first derivative test, this is a maximum or minimum, depending on the sign of <m>a</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Determining concavity, <m>f''(x) = 2a</m> which is constant. If <m>a > 0</m>, then <m>f''(x) > 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, and <m>f</m> is concave up. If <m>a \lt 0</m>, then <m>f'' \lt 0</m>, and <m>f</m> is concave down.
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Cubic Polynomials</title>
        <p>
            Note that a cubic function always has exactly one point of inflection, because the second derivative is a linear function, which has one root.
        </p>
        <p>
            Note that a polynomial function of degree <m>n</m> can have at most <m>n-1</m> relative extrema, and at most <m>n-2</m> inflection points.
        </p>
        <p>
            If a polynomial has a double root, then it has a horizontal tangent there (like the function <m>f(x) = x^3</m>).
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Sketching the Graph of a Rational Function</title>
        <p>
            The procedure for a rational function is somewhat similar to that of a polynomial function, except with rational functions we have a few extra characteristics.
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>Rational functions can have values of <m>x</m> where <m>f'(x)</m> does not exist (critical numbers), or where <m>f''(x)</m> does not exist.</li>
            <li>Rational functions have can have horizontal and vertical asymptotes, and may have holes.</li>
        </ol>
    </subsection>

